2026-05-06 | Count Ways to Place Two Knights So They Do Not Attack

	Question
Return the number of valid placements.
	Key Insight
First count all possible placements.
Total squares:
		n × m
Choose 2 different squares:
		total =
		(n*m)*(n*m-1)/2
Now subtract attacking placements.
A knight attack occurs inside:
		2 × 3 rectangle
		or
		3 × 2 rectangle
In every such rectangle:
		exactly 2 attacking pairs exist.
Number of 2×3 rectangles:
		(n-1)*(m-2)
Number of 3×2 rectangles:
		(n-2)*(m-1)
Therefore:
		attackingPairs =
		2 * (
			(n-1)*(m-2)
			+
			(n-2)*(m-1)
		)
Answer:
		total - attackingPairs
	Approach
1.	Compute total ways to place two knights.
2.	Compute number of attacking pairs.
3.	Subtract attacking pairs from total.
4.	Return result.
	Time Complexity
	O(1)
	Space Complexity
	O(1)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    long long knightInGeekland(long long n, long long m) {
        long long cells = n * m;
        long long totalWays =
            cells * (cells - 1) / 2;
        long long attackingPairs = 0;
        if(n >= 2 && m >= 3)
            attackingPairs +=
                2LL * (n - 1) * (m - 2);
        if(n >= 3 && m >= 2)
            attackingPairs +=
                2LL * (n - 2) * (m - 1);
        return totalWays - attackingPairs;
    }
};
	Key Insight
Instead of trying to count all non-attacking placements directly, count:
		all possible placements
and subtract:
		all attacking placements.
The attacking pairs can be counted mathematically using the number of 2×3 and 3×2 rectangles on the board, giving an O(1) solution.
